<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2010/08/23/fantod/ea58c341-5fed-409d-ab79-e11f9608f8cf/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/fantod" title="User profile page">fantod</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">13 November 2010 2:49AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>Scary, scary story. I'm a fairly avid mushroom hunter, but I dread being poisoned so I restrict myself to two or three species that cannot be confused with any local poisonous ones. Fortunately my area is flush with chanterelles, my favourite, and morels can be had in abundance too.</p><p><b>@GreatGrandDad:</b><br>Re: Southeast Asians and mushrooms: back in the early 90s there was a rash of fatal poisonings among SE Asian immigrants, mostly Hmong and Lao,  in the US Pacific Northwest. Apparently they had eaten wild mushrooms that resembled edible species from back home. Tricky things, those 'shrooms.</p>
						
					</div>
