			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-8372696">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2010/08/23/therentedhat/c2237c0f-294b-454d-ab60-ed383a0add11/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/therentedhat" title="User profile page">therentedhat</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">13 November 2010 7:54AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>Wild mushroom picking should be a slow, leisurely activity performed by people that know what they are doing (the author took a class during college on mushroom foraging?  I took two classes on German in college, I can't speak a word of it ten years later and I'm definitely not working on my translation of Goethe's Faust).  You don't go mushroom picking before the kids football match or before the BBQ in the afternoon.   In the article I saw words that denote impatience, like, "I was in a rush because I'm going out."  Hate to say it, but you know....</p><p>I'm going to defer to Karl Pilkington when he discussed the Japanese eating blowfish.  "If it can kill you, don't eat it.  Have some chicken instead."  Unless you really know what your doing, don't bother.  I know a farmer that does some foraging (the guy knows what he's doing) and he told me that his liability insurance for the wild mushroom picking and retailing was larger than his liability insurance for his entire farm (80-100 acre commercial apple orchard about an hour south of Ithica by car).  Think about it.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
