			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-8372703">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/genoa1893" title="User profile page">genoa1893</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">13 November 2010 7:57AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>Books can't teach you how to pick mushrooms. As someone who was born in Italy, where mushroom picking is a quasi-sport, you quickly learn that mushrooms, due to environmental reasons can change in colour and aspect quite significantly.</p><p> Only years of experience can make you 100% sure of what you pick. I for instace pick no more than 10 varieties (Russulas, Boletus Edulis and its related varieties, Amanita Cesarea, some Lactarius in pine woods and that's about it). I was taught to recognise them by my dad who in turn was taught by my grandad: foolproof methods. I read many books but none of them has persuaded me to pick other species no matter how interesting they were, I just do not feel confident enough because I know a night of rain, a few leaves and a bit of win can make a poisonus mushroom look like its closely related edible one.</p><p> My English partner is often amazed by my prudence as I guide her through the different species:</p><p>her: Is this good?<br>me: Yes I think so, I am pretty sure is not poisonus, but I am not 100% sure so leave it.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
