			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-8372713">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/grandbornand" title="User profile page">grandbornand</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">13 November 2010 7:59AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>picking wild mushrooms is quite safe if you know what you are doing. that means learning key identifiers (size, colour, gill shape, spore print etc.) by book or with people you trust until you learn to recognise them by eye (and even then if not sure do test or don't eat).</p><p>whatever you do don't believe any "folklore short-cuts" i.e. "if nibbled at already they must be edible ones"; "red ones are poisonous" etc. they are all rubbish. saffron milkcaps (edibles which grown with pine) are orange and give off a green milk! yellow staining agaric looks identical to field mushroom but is poisonous (except if stains yellow when cut and smells bad when you cook it, so that should avoid mistakes)</p><p>the guy here was an idiot and lucky he came out alive. my mum lives in french alps next to a lake. when i was last there we had a very severe storm with high winds. from house we could see a helicopter flying around lake. this was odd as were very dangerous conditions for flying. next day we found out a man in his 50s (married with 3 kids) had drowned while wanting to test how his new kayak in extreme conditions...</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
