			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-8372821">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/johntherock" title="User profile page">johntherock</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">13 November 2010 8:25AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>The key skill to develop if you are going to eat wild mushrooms is to learn to automatically recognise the dozen or so very toxic ones at a glance.</p><p>Although many others are edible, I've become inclined to stick to just a few: chanterelles, hedgehog fungus, field mushrooms, ceps and parasols. All are distinctive and all are delicious.</p><p>Interesting story, though - and he was wise to question what he had eaten. With some Amanitas, the patient appears to make a recovery from the gastrointestinal stage of poisoning and the organ failure kicks in a week or two later as a second, deadly phase. It's due to the toxins recycling themselves around the body rather than being expelled, so that the damage builds up progressively.</p><p>Cheers - John</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
