			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-8373242">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2010/08/23/flynnjed/b1df7e32-0eae-4c8b-9da6-f0017c032528/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/flynnjed" title="User profile page">flynnjed</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">13 November 2010 9:29AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>Sorry to be pedantic but there's no such thing as a mushroom the 'looks poisonous'. What is  a poisonous mushroom supposed to look like? Glowing red with a skull an crossbones on it? </p><p>Some the most poisonous ones look bland and reassuring - some of the best edible ones look distinctly odd and strange.</p><p>But how can you confuse a destroying angel with an ink cap? - they're both whitish and have caps and stems - there ends the similarities.</p><p>What's more the poison in some mushrooms is not a defensive measure but rather a by product of its metabolism - mushrooms don't care much whether they're eaten or not.</p><p>There are no rules that can be applied as to whether a mushroom is poisonous or not - the only way to know is to identify it accurately.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
